The integration fixture, written mainly in Scala.

The frontmatter above names the primary language. Every heading below is a
flat Section — heading level is reader-facing organisation only, the tree
stays flat.

# Reading notes

A heading at any level creates a flat Section.

=>

val readingNote = "Sections are flat on the document"

~

This prose line still belongs to the Reading notes Section.

# Glossary

A Section named after its title. Every Section has an identifier, the
title normalised — `Glossary` becomes `Glossary`.

# Arithmetic

A library of integer arithmetic. The primitives first, a couple of
composites on top, and a `main` that prints a few results.

## Imports

`Math.pow` is the only outside dependency.

=>

import scala.math.pow

~

Everything else is in the standard library.

## Adder

=>

def add(x: Int, y: Int): Int = x + y

## Multiplier

=>

def mul(x: Int, y: Int): Int = x * y

## Square

Built on top of the multiplier section, named by its title.

=>

::[Multiplier]

def square(x: Int): Int = mul(x, x)

## Power

`pow` works in `Double`; the result is rounded back to `Int`.

=>

def power(base: Int, exp: Int): Int = pow(base, exp).toInt

## Entry point

Smoke tests over the primitives and composites, each named by its title.

=>

::[Adder]
::[Square]
::[Power]

object Arithmetic extends App {
  println(s"add(2, 3)    = ${add(2, 3)}")
  println(s"mul(4, 5)    = ${mul(4, 5)}")
  println(s"square(7)    = ${square(7)}")
  println(s"power(2, 10) = ${power(2, 10)}")
}

# Tuning

{{rounds = 3}}

A value Warp binds a literal its anchors compose. `::[rounds]` writes the
value `3` where the anchor stands.

=>

val rounds: Int = ::[rounds]

# Build script {Bash}

Compile the single file, then run the resulting class.

=>

#!/usr/bin/env bash
scalac src/main/scala/Arithmetic.scala -d out
scala -cp out Arithmetic

